messages.say:
Thought for 1m 40s


Your current per-header definition has 5 sections:


value_schema, scope, presence, normalization, provenance


It has no place to specify how the value is produced. If you want “how the header value is derived/populated/calculated” to be first-class and machine-enforceable, you need to add a 6th section per header, e.g. derivation.


Add this field to every header: derivation


Minimal required shape (per header)


"derivation": {
  "mode": "LITERAL | INPUT | EXTRACTED | LOOKUP | DERIVED | AGGREGATED | SYSTEM",
  "sources": [
    {
      "kind": "COLUMN | FILESYSTEM | REGISTRY | CONSTANT | ENV | TOOL_OUTPUT",
      "ref": "string",
      "path": "string (optional JSONPointer/JSONPath-like)"
    }
  ],
  "process": {
    "engine": "NONE | TRANSFORM_CHAIN | FORMULA_AST | LOOKUP_SPEC | TASK_OUTPUT",
    "spec": {}
  },
  "null_policy": "ALLOW_NULL | COERCE_DEFAULT | ERROR",
  "error_policy": "ERROR | WARN | NULL",
  "evidence": {
    "evidence_keys": [],
    "artifacts": []
  }
}


What each piece means


mode: category of how the value appears.
INPUT: user/hand-entered (still validated)

EXTRACTED: pulled directly from a source (filesystem scan, parsing a file, etc.)

LOOKUP: retrieved from a registry/map using a key

DERIVED: computed from other fields via a formula

AGGREGATED: computed across rows (counts, group-by, etc.)

SYSTEM: injected by runtime (timestamps, run IDs, etc.)

LITERAL: constant

sources: explicit dependencies (what this value depends on).

process.engine + process.spec: the actual deterministic algorithm/formula (structured, not vibes).

null_policy / error_policy: what happens when inputs missing or computation fails.

evidence: what artifacts/log keys prove the value was computed correctly.


Representing the “actual formula/process” (no free-form strings)


Option A: Formula as an AST (recommended)


Instead of "formula": "a + b" (ambiguous), use a structured AST:


"process": {
  "engine": "FORMULA_AST",
  "spec": {
    "op": "concat",
    "args": [
      { "op": "col", "name": "parent_dir" },
      { "op": "lit", "value": "/" },
      { "op": "col", "name": "file_name" }
    ]
  }
}


This is deterministic and schema-validatable.


Option B: Lookup spec (for registry-derived fields)


"process": {
  "engine": "LOOKUP_SPEC",
  "spec": {
    "registry_ref": "governance/geu_registry.json",
    "key": { "op": "col", "name": "file_id" },
    "lookup_path_template": "/members/{key}/geu_role"
  }
}


Option C: Task output binding (pipeline-produced fields)


"process": {
  "engine": "TASK_OUTPUT",
  "spec": {
    "task_id": "TASK_FS_SCAN_010",
    "output_key": "absolute_path",
    "evidence_artifact": "EVIDENCE_FS_SCAN_JSONL"
  }
}


Concrete per-header examples


1) absolute_path (extracted from filesystem scan)


"absolute_path": {
  "value_schema": { "type": ["string","null"] },
  "scope": { "record_kinds_in": ["FILE"], "entity_kinds_in": ["FILE"] },
  "presence": { "policy": "REQUIRED", "rules": [] },
  "normalization": { "transforms": ["norm_path_abs"] },
  "provenance": { "sources": [] },
  "derivation": {
    "mode": "EXTRACTED",
    "sources": [{ "kind": "FILESYSTEM", "ref": "scan_event.path" }],
    "process": { "engine": "TASK_OUTPUT", "spec": { "task_id": "TASK_FS_SCAN_010", "output_key": "absolute_path" } },
    "null_policy": "ERROR",
    "error_policy": "ERROR",
    "evidence": { "evidence_keys": ["fs_scan.event_id"], "artifacts": ["EVIDENCE_FS_SCAN_JSONL"] }
  }
}


2) geu_role (lookup from GEU registry using file_id)


"geu_role": {
  "...": "...",
  "derivation": {
    "mode": "LOOKUP",
    "sources": [
      { "kind": "COLUMN", "ref": "file_id" },
      { "kind": "REGISTRY", "ref": "governance/geu_registry.json" }
    ],
    "process": {
      "engine": "LOOKUP_SPEC",
      "spec": {
        "registry_ref": "governance/geu_registry.json",
        "key": { "op": "col", "name": "file_id" },
        "lookup_path_template": "/files/{key}/geu_role"
      }
    },
    "null_policy": "ALLOW_NULL",
    "error_policy": "WARN",
    "evidence": { "evidence_keys": ["geu_registry.checksum"], "artifacts": ["EVIDENCE_REGISTRY_SNAPSHOT"] }
  }
}


3) allocated_at (system-injected timestamp)


"allocated_at": {
  "...": "...",
  "derivation": {
    "mode": "SYSTEM",
    "sources": [{ "kind": "ENV", "ref": "generated_utc" }],
    "process": { "engine": "NONE", "spec": {} },
    "null_policy": "ERROR",
    "error_policy": "ERROR",
    "evidence": { "evidence_keys": ["run_id"], "artifacts": ["EVIDENCE_RUN_META_JSON"] }
  }
}


Enforceability rules (so it’s not just documentation)


To make this “teeth,” your validator should enforce:


Every header must include derivation.

mode=DERIVED ⇒ process.engine=FORMULA_AST and sources must include all referenced col nodes.

mode=LOOKUP ⇒ registry_ref, key, and lookup_path_template required.

mode=TASK_OUTPUT ⇒ task_id, output_key, and evidence artifact required.

null_policy=ERROR ⇒ header presence.policy should not be OPTIONAL unless explicitly conditional.


If you want, I can give you a JSON Schema fragment for headers.*.derivation that enforces the mode→required-fields matrix (oneOf branches), matching this structure.
